==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Predestinate
<hw>Pre*des"ti*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>praedestinatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>praedestinare</ets> to
predestine; <ets>prae</ets> before + <ets>destinare</ets> to determine.
See <er>Destine</er>.]</ety> <def>Predestinated; foreordained;
fated.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>predestinate</xex> scratched face.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Predestinate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Predestinate
<hw>Pre*des"ti*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Predestinated</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Predestinating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Predestine</er>.]</ety> <def>To predetermine or foreordain; to
appoint or ordain beforehand by an unchangeable purpose or decree; to
pre⟦eum⟧lect.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whom he did foreknow, he also did <qex>predestinate</qex> to be
conformed to the image of his Son.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. viii.
29.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To predetermine; foreordain; preordain; decree;
predestine; foredoom.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Predestination</ent>⟦br⟧
